  "doc_id": "17725",
  "text": "ROS generation in response to mechanical forces may originate from several sources, including the NOX, xanthine oxidase, or other oxidase systems, such as nitric oxide oxidase, and mitochondria. Our results with the NOX inhibitor apocynin suggest an involvement of this source of ROS. Owing to its overexpression in dystrophic heart [CITATION_1] and due to its rapid activation by osmotic swelling, [CITATION_2] this source of ROS may be particularly important in the early phases of the response. It is also established that an elevation in mitochondrial [Ca 2þ ] subsequent to prolonged cytosolic Ca 2þ signal activity stimulates mitochondrial ROS production. [CITATION_3] Consistent with this notion, we observed increased Ca 2þ levels in cardiac mitochondria following the osmotic shock that were significantly larger in mdx cells. [CITATION_4] On the other hand, CICR and elevated [Ca 2þ ] i favour mitochondrial ROS production, as discussed above. Taken together, the simultaneous activation of these signalling pathways is particularly destructive for the cells because it has a tendency to escalate into mutually synergistic positive feed-back signalling loops.",
